was an old man.

01:59.840 --> 02:03.400
Now, back then,
Jaguar won Le Mans
three times with the D-Type.

02:03.440 --> 02:05.120
And after they retired
that from racing,

02:05.160 --> 02:08.520
they decided to build
25 road-going versions of it,

02:08.560 --> 02:10.720
which they called the XKSS.

02:10.760 --> 02:12.640
We've got a photograph
of one here.

02:12.680 --> 02:16.120
Now, this was aimed
at wealthy young gentlemen

02:16.160 --> 02:18.720
who wanted to spend the week
dashing around town

02:18.760 --> 02:21.640
and then the weekend
doing motor racing.

02:21.680 --> 02:25.840
Steve McQueen had one,
and I think that says it all.

02:25.880 --> 02:30.080
Unfortunately,
in 1957 there was
a huge fire at the factory,

02:30.120 --> 02:35.480
and nine of those 25 cars
were never made& until now.

02:51.960 --> 02:54.840
Let me make one thing plain
right from the start -

02:54.880 --> 02:59.840
this is not a replica XKSS
built from plastic,

02:59.880 --> 03:02.040
this is an XKSS.

03:08.400 --> 03:14.080
Built by Jaguar themselves
over 10,000 painstaking
hours, it's the real deal.

03:16.520 --> 03:20.480
In fact, it's as real
as the real ones
from way back when.

03:31.640 --> 03:35.760
The chassis is made from
a special steel
called Reynolds 531.

03:35.800 --> 03:38.760
It's what they
originally used to build
the World War II Spitfire.

03:38.800 --> 03:41.840
And it's light -
it only weighs 39kg.

03:41.880 --> 03:43.960
And then there's the body.

03:44.000 --> 03:47.000
The tooling and
the technical drawings were
all destroyed in the fire,

03:47.040 --> 03:50.160
so they had to scan
an original from 1957

03:50.200 --> 03:52.960
and then work backwards
from that to make it,

03:53.000 --> 03:55.440
in incredible detail,
right down to the rivets.

03:55.480 --> 03:59.160
Every one, the number and
the position is as it was.

03:59.200 --> 04:02.080
And there's
over 2,000 of them.

04:02.120 --> 04:05.960
But it was the engine
that was the trickiest bit.

04:06.000 --> 04:08.600
The plans for that weren't
destroyed in the fire -

04:08.640 --> 04:13.240
in fact, I've got
a copy of them here -
but there was a page missing.

04:13.280 --> 04:15.240
So they had to get
an original engine

04:15.280 --> 04:18.400
and saw it in half
to find out how it worked.

04:20.480 --> 04:24.240
No-one has ever made
a car like this before.

04:24.280 --> 04:26.560
It's a world first.

04:26.600 --> 04:32.440
So it's small wonder
it's priced at just over
one million pounds.

04:35.480 --> 04:38.640
Or, for half a million pounds
more,

04:38.680 --> 04:40.480
you can have one of these!

04:45.280 --> 04:49.920
It's an Aston Martin DB4
GT Lightweight.

04:49.960 --> 04:55.120
And back in the late '50s,
it was the fastest car
in the world.

04:56.480 --> 05:00.760
Flat out, it would do 151mph.

05:08.160 --> 05:12.120
